----------------------- DESCRIPTION -------------------------------

The goal of this project is to measure a LiPo battery's voltage using an STM32 NUCLEO-G474RE, calculate the estimated battery percentage, and send this information via a CAN bus.

It was build using VScode based on a STM32cubeMX configurated file.

---------------------- PCB PROJECT LINK ---------------------------

 https://oshwlab.com/ewen.coubel-etes/project_nwfmnrfi

--------------------- ADDITIONNAL DISPLAY -------------------------

The project also provides feedback through an optional I2C screen to display the following information:
1st screen: ADC raw value, calculated voltage, estimated battery percentage, and CAN status.
2nd screen: CAN debug information.
The switch between both displays occurs when the CAN status is different from OK or PENDING.

// You can enable the CAN debug information by setting the "ACTIVATE_CAN_DEBUG_SCREEN" variable to 1 in CAN_exchange.h
// You can disable the CAN debug information by setting the "ACTIVATE_CAN_DEBUG_SCREEN" variable to 0 in CAN_exchange.h

----------------- LIPO BATTERY CONFIGURATION ----------------------

The project supports 1S to 4S LiPo battery configurations.
To select your battery configuration, change the value of "CURRENT_BATTERY_TYPE".
The expected definition must be in this format: "BATTERY_TYPE_XS", where X is 1, 2, 3, or 4.

As the STM32 ADC only support 0-3.3V input, the value must be downsized using a voltage divider. The value of this voltage divider must be specified in "battery_profile.h" in the "VOLTAGE_DIVIDER_RATIO   0.21259843f" where "0.21259843f" is the divider value.

------------------- CAN BUS CONFIGURATION -------------------------

The CAN bus is configured with a 125k baud rate and an 87.5% sample point.
To change the CAN configuration, go to "CAN_exchange.c" and modify these values:

// Nominal bit timing configuration
hfdcan1.Init.NominalPrescaler     = 85U;
hfdcan1.Init.NominalTimeSeg1      = 13U;
hfdcan1.Init.NominalTimeSeg2      = 2U;
hfdcan1.Init.NominalSyncJumpWidth = 1U;

The method to calculate the bitrate and sample point can be found in the dedicated section of "CAN_exchange.c"..
To change the configuration of the CAN go to : "CAN_exchange.c" and modify those value :

          // Nominal bit timing configuration
          hfdcan1.Init.NominalPrescaler     = 85U;
          hfdcan1.Init.NominalTimeSeg1      = 13U;
          hfdcan1.Init.NominalTimeSeg2      = 2U;
          hfdcan1.Init.NominalSyncJumpWidth = 1U;

The way to calculate the bitrate and sample point is in CAN_exchange, at the featured area.

---------------- DBC READING CAN BUS INFORMATIONS ----------------

If you want to read the raw CAN bus informations, you can use Linux "can-utils" library and the DBC file with the can-utils library along with the cantools project available here : https://github.com/cantools/cantools

After installation : 
// To launch the can connection : (make sure to change "can0" to match your can interface number)
sudo ip link set can0 up type can bitrate 125000 sample-point 0.875

// To read the sended values :
candump can0 | cantools decode project_can.dbc

// The output should looks like : 
 can0  123   [3]  2D 00 00 ::
Battery_Voltage_Message(
    voltage_millivolt: 45 mV,
    percentage: 0 %
)

------------------- PIN OUT CONFIGURATION ----------------------

input : 

The ADC is on CN9 A0 pin - GPIO_A_0

output :

// To the CAN transceiver
The TX is on CN10 pin 12 - GPIO_A_12
The RX in on CN10 pin 14 - GPIO_A_11

// To the I2C 128x64 Oled screen
The SCL is on CN5 D15 pin - GPIO_B_9
The SDA is on CN5 D14 pin _ GPIO_B_8

------------------- FLASHING THE PROJECT -----------------------

// In the same directory as the Makefile use command :
make clean && make && make flash
// The generated file will be called "voltmeter", you can file it in the build folder.
